{"title":"A Simple Single-Scale Vision Transformer for Object Detection and Instance Segmentation","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Modern ViT backbones for detection/segmentation often import CNN-style multistage designs (spatial downsampling, multi-scale features, doubled channels), but their actual benefits for transformers on dense prediction are unclear, and they add complexity.","method":"Propose Universal Vision Transformer (UViT), a vanilla ViT backbone that keeps constant token resolution and hidden size through all encoder blocks and outputs a single-scale feature map to standard heads (no spatial downsampling, no multi-scale features from the backbone, no channel-doubling). Through controlled COCO ablations under matched params/FLOPs, they show these CNN-like add-ons are unnecessary and often hurt, with the simple single-scale ViT performing best. UViT achieves competitive accuracy with far fewer parameters than hierarchical ViTs (e.g., UViT-B: 52.3 AP with 74.4M params vs Swin-B: 51.9 AP with 145M; same Cascade Mask R-CNN)."},{"problem":"Choosing how to scale ViTs (depth, width, input size) for dense prediction is underexplored and differs from CNN scaling laws, impacting the accuracy–efficiency trade-off.","method":"Systematically study compound scaling of UViT across input sizes (640–1024), depths (12–40 blocks), and widths under fixed windowed attention and ImageNet-1k pretraining. Findings: larger input sizes create more headroom, with 896×896 consistently offering a better trade-off than smaller sizes and slightly better than 1024×1024 in comparable FLOPs; a moderate depth of 18 blocks yields better performance-efficiency than shallower (12) or deeper (24/32/40) models. They instantiate UViT-T/S/B at 18 layers with increasing widths, forming a compact, strong backbone series for COCO fine-tuning."},{"problem":"Global self-attention on high-resolution inputs is computationally expensive and may be unnecessary in early layers if those layers mostly attend locally.","method":"Measure relative attention receptive fields of a pretrained ViT on COCO and observe early layers act locally while deeper layers become global. Based on this, use attention windows to limit attention range: a constant local window (e.g., 1/2 scale) already preserves accuracy with large compute savings; further, a progressive schedule that uses small windows in early blocks and grows to global windows only in the last blocks (UViT+) reduces FLOPs while maintaining or improving AP. For example, UViT-B+: 52.5 AP at 1160 GFLOPs vs UViT-B: 52.3 AP at 1298.7 GFLOPs; early over-shrinking (e.g., 1/16, 1/8) hurts, and global windows in deep layers are vital."}]}
